Definition 2.1 A Cartesian category $\mathbb{X}$ is said to have a system of linear maps, ${\cal L}$, in case in each simple slice $\mathbb{X}[A]$ there is a system of maps ${\cal L}[A]\subseteq\mathbb{X}[A]$, which we shall refer to as the ${\cal L}[A]$-linear maps (or, when $\cal L$ is understood, simply as “linear” maps), satisfying: [LS.1] for each $X,Y,Z\in\mathbb{X}[A]$, all of $1_{X},\pi_{0}:X\times Y\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}X,\pi_{1}:X\times Y\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox t% o 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}Y$ are in ${\cal L}[A]$ and, furthermore, $\langle f,g\rangle:X\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}Y\times Z\in{\cal L}[A]$ whenever $f,g\in{\cal L}[A]$; [LS.2] in each $\mathbb{X}[A]$, ${\cal L}[A]$, as a system of maps, is closed under composition, furthermore, whenever $g\in{\cal L}[A]$ is a retraction and $gh\in{\cal L}[A]$ then $h\in{\cal L}[A]$; [LS.3] all substitution functors $\infer{\mathbb{X}[B]\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 32.99968pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits_{\hbox{\scriptsize$\mathbb{X}[f]$}}}\mathbb{X}[A]}{A% \allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 17.24992pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits^{% \hbox{\scriptsize$f$}}}B}$ preserve linear maps.
Definition 7.1. The Burnside category $\mathcal{B}_{G}$ is a category whose objects are finite $G$-sets and whose morphisms arise from spans of finite $G$-sets: Given $G$-sets $A$ and $B$, a span from $A$ to $B$ is a diagram of the form $A\leftarrow C\to B$ where $C$ is also a finite $G$-set and both maps are equivariant. Note that such a diagram is equivalent to a map $C\to B\times A$ as well. An isomorphism of spans is a diagram of the form: $\xymatrix@R=1.25pc{&C\ar[dl]\ar[dr]\ar[dd]^{\cong}\\ A&&B\\ &D\ar[ul]\ar[ur]}$ Spans from $A$ to $B$ have a monoidal product given by disjoint union in the source of the two maps of the span, and the morphisms in $\mathcal{B}_{G}$ are defined to be the group completion of the abelian monoid of isomorphism classes of spans. Composition is given by pullback of spans. These morphisms make $\mathcal{B}_{G}$ into an additive category.
Definition 9.1. Let $S_{X}\colon G\mathcal{E}^{\text{op}}\to Perm$ be the representable functor given by the finite $G$-set $X\in G\mathcal{E}$. That is, for any $A\in G\mathcal{E}$, $S_{X}(A)=G\mathcal{E}^{\text{op}}(X,A)=G\mathcal{E}(A,X)$ which is a permutative category since $G\mathcal{E}$ is a $\mathbf{PC}$-category. On morphisms, this functor is given by the unique strictly unital symmetric monoidal functor $S_{X}\colon G\mathcal{E}^{\text{op}}(A,B)\to Perm(G\mathcal{E}^{\text{op}}(X,A% ),G\mathcal{E}^{\text{op}}(X,B))$ which Lemma 5.3 produces from the bilinear composition map $\textrm{comp}\colon(G\mathcal{E}^{\text{op}}(A,B),G\mathcal{E}^{\text{op}}(X,A% ))\to G\mathcal{E}^{\text{op}}(X,B).$
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ be permutative categories. A strictly unital lax symmetric monoidal functor $(f,\delta)\colon\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ consists of a functor $f\colon\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ of underlying categories, together with a natural transformation $\delta\colon f(a)\oplus f(a^{\prime})\to f(a\oplus a^{\prime}),$ called the structure morphism. This data must satisfy the following conditions: (1) $f(0)=0$; (2) if either $a$ or $a^{\prime}$ is 0, then $\delta$ is the identity morphism; (3) for all $a,a^{\prime},a^{\prime\prime}\in\mathcal{A}$ , the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix{f(a)\oplus f(a^{\prime})\oplus f(a^{\prime\prime})\ar[r]^{-}{\textrm% {id}\oplus\delta}\ar[d]_{\delta\oplus\textrm{id}}&f(a)\oplus f(a^{\prime}% \oplus a^{\prime\prime})\ar[d]^{\delta}\\ f(a\oplus a^{\prime})\oplus f(a^{\prime\prime})\ar[r]_{-}{\delta}&f(a\oplus a^% {\prime}\oplus a^{\prime\prime});}$ (4) for all $a,a^{\prime}\in\mathcal{A}$, the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix{f(a)\oplus f(a^{\prime})\ar[r]^{-}{\delta}\ar[d]_{\gamma}&f(a\oplus a% ^{\prime})\ar[d]^{f(\gamma)}\\ f(a^{\prime})\oplus f(a)\ar[r]_{-}{\delta}&f(a^{\prime}\oplus a).}$
Definition 7.3. Let $G\mathcal{B}$ denote the spectrally enriched Burnside category $\mathbb{K}_{\bullet}G\mathcal{E}$.
Definition 3.5. Let $\underline{Perm}$ be the multicategory whose objects are small permutative categories and whose multimorphisms are given by multilinear functors between them. A 0-morphism $a\colon()\to\mathcal{A}$ is given by a choice of object $a$ in $\mathcal{A}$. Given multilinear functors $(g;\{\delta_{j}^{g}\}_{j=1}^{n})\colon(\mathcal{B}_{1},\dots,\mathcal{B}_{n})% \to\mathcal{C}$ and $(f_{j};\{\delta^{f_{j}}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{k_{j}})\colon(\mathcal{A}_{j}^{1},\dots,% \mathcal{A}_{j}^{k_{j}})\to B_{j}$ for $j=1,\dots,n$, we define their composite by $(g;\{\delta_{j}^{g}\}_{j=1}^{n})\circ\left((f_{1};\{\delta^{f_{1}}_{i}\}_{i=1}% ^{k_{1}}),\dots,(f_{n};\{\delta^{f_{n}}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{k_{n}})\right)=(g\circ(f_% {1}\times\cdots\times f_{n});(\delta_{s})_{s=1}^{\sum k_{j}})$ where $\delta_{s}$ is given by the appropriate composite of $\delta_{j}^{g}$ with $g(\delta_{i}^{f_{j}})$. See [EM06, Definition 3.2] for details.
Definition 2.7. Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be $\mathcal{M}$-enriched categories. An $\mathcal{M}$-enriched functor $F\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ consists of an assignment $F\colon ob\mathcal{C}\to ob\mathcal{D}$, and for each pair of objects $a$ and $b$ in $\mathcal{C}$, a morphism in $\mathcal{M}$, $F\colon\mathcal{C}(a,b)\to\mathcal{D}(Fa,Fb),$ compatible with composition and identity, as expressed by the commutativity of the diagrams $\xymatrix{(\mathcal{C}(b,c),\mathcal{C}(a,b))\ar[r]^{-}{\textrm{comp}}\ar[d]_{% (F,F)}&\mathcal{C}(a,c)\ar[d]^{F}\\ (\mathcal{D}(Fb,Fc),\mathcal{D}(Fa,Fb))\ar[r]_{-}{\textrm{comp}}&\mathcal{D}(% Fa,Fc),}$ and $\xymatrix{()\ar[r]^{-}{\textrm{id}_{a}}\ar[dr]_{-}{\textrm{id}_{Fa}}&\mathcal{% C}(a,a)\ar[d]^{F}\\ &\mathcal{D}(Fa,Fa).}$
Definition 7.2. The $\mathbf{PC}$-category $G\mathcal{E}$ has finite $G$-sets as objects. If $A$ and $B$ are finite $G$-sets, the permutative category of morphisms $G\mathcal{E}(A,B)$ is the category of spans of finite $G$-sets from $A$ to $B$ and isomorphisms of spans. The permutative structure is given by disjoint union. Composition is given by pullback, where we make the following explicit choices. Let $A\xrightarrow{f}B\xleftarrow{f^{\prime}}C$ be a diagram of $G$-maps. If $f$ is the identity, choose the pullback $B\times_{B}C=C$ and if $f^{\prime}$ is the identity, choose the pullback $A\times_{B}B=A$. These specific choices of pullbacks along identity maps make composition strictly unital. If neither $f$ nor $f^{\prime}$ is the identity, choose the pullback $A\times_{B}C$ to be the subset of $A\times C$ picked out by the pullback condition, where the set $A\times C$ is given lexicographical ordering. Together these choices ensure that composition in $G\mathcal{E}$ is strictly associative.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathcal{A}_{1},\dots,\mathcal{A}_{k}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ be permutative categories. A multilinear functor $(f;\delta_{1},\dots\delta_{k})\colon(\mathcal{A}_{1},\dots,\mathcal{A}_{k})\to% \mathcal{B}$ consists of a functor $f\colon\mathcal{A}_{1}\times\cdots\times\mathcal{A}_{k}\to\mathcal{B}$ of underlying categories, together with natural transformations $\delta_{i}\colon f(a_{1},\dots,a_{i},\dots,a_{k})\oplus f(a_{1},\dots,a^{% \prime}_{i},\dots,a_{k})\to f(a_{1},\dots,a_{i}\oplus a^{\prime}_{i},\dots,a_{% k})$ called linearity constraints. These constraints must satisfy conditions given in [EM06, Definition 3.2]. In particular, $f(a_{1},\dotsc,a_{k})=0$ if any $a_{j}=0$. Additionally, the transformation $\delta_{i}$ is the identity map if either $a_{i}$, $a_{i}^{\prime}$ or any other $a_{j}$ is $0$.
Definition 2.5. An $\mathcal{M}$-enriched category $\mathcal{C}$ consists of a collection of objects, $ob\mathcal{C}$, and for objects $a,b$ in $\mathcal{C}$, a morphism object $\mathcal{C}(a,b)$ which is an object of $\mathcal{M}$. For objects $a,b,c$ of $\mathcal{C}$, composition is given by a 2-morphism in $\mathcal{M}$, $\textrm{comp}\colon(\mathcal{C}(b,c),\mathcal{C}(a,b))\to\mathcal{C}(a,c),$ and the identity is given by a 0-morphism in $\mathcal{M}$ with the empty sequence as source, $\textrm{id}_{a}\colon()\to\mathcal{C}(a,a).$ These morphisms are subject to the usual associativity and identity constraints, which are expressed as follows. Given objects $a,b,c,d$ in $\mathcal{C}$, the following diagram in $\mathcal{M}$ commutes: $\xymatrixcolsep{2cm}\xymatrix{(\mathcal{C}(c,d),\mathcal{C}(b,c),\mathcal{C}(a% ,b))\ar[r]^{-}{(\textrm{comp},1_{\mathcal{C}(a,b)})}\ar[d]_{(1_{\mathcal{C}(c,% d)},\textrm{comp})}&(\mathcal{C}(b,d),\mathcal{C}(a,b))\ar[d]^{\textrm{comp}}% \\ (\mathcal{C}(c,d),\mathcal{C}(a,c))\ar[r]_{-}{\textrm{comp}}&\mathcal{C}(a,d).}$ For objects $a$ and $b$, the diagram $\xymatrixcolsep{2cm}\xymatrixrowsep{1.5cm}\xymatrix{(\mathcal{C}(a,b))\ar[r]^{% -}{(\textrm{id}_{b},1_{\mathcal{C}(a,b)})}\ar[d]_{(1_{\mathcal{C}(a,b)},% \textrm{id}_{a})}\ar[rd]^{-}{1_{\mathcal{C}(a,b)}}&(\mathcal{C}(b,b),\mathcal{% C}(a,b))\ar[d]^{\textrm{comp}}\\ (\mathcal{C}(a,b),\mathcal{C}(a,a))\ar[r]_{-}{\textrm{comp}}&\mathcal{C}(a,b)}$ commutes.
Definition 2.1. A multicategory $\mathcal{M}$ consists of a collection of objects, denoted $ob\mathcal{M}$, and for each $k\geq 0$ and objects $a_{1},\cdots a_{k},b$, a set $\mathcal{M}(a_{1},\dots,a_{k};b)$ of $k$-morphisms $(a_{1},\dots,a_{k})\to b$. The morphism sets are related by composition functions $\xymatrix{\makebox[86.724pt]{$\mathcal{M}(b_{1},\dots b_{n};c)\times\mathcal{M% }(a_{1}^{1},\dots,a_{1}^{k_{1}};b_{1})\times\cdots\times\mathcal{M}(a_{n}^{1},% \dots,a_{n}^{k_{n}};b_{n})$}\ar[d]\\ \mathcal{M}(a_{1}^{1},\dots,a_{1}^{k_{1}},\dots,a_{n}^{1},\dots,a_{n}^{k_{n}};% c).}$ These functions are denoted by $(g;f_{1},\dots f_{n})\mapsto g\circ(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})$. For each object $a$, there is an identity morphism $1_{a}\in\mathcal{M}(a;a)$. All of this data is subject to associativity and identity conditions, which can be found in [Lei04, §2.1].
Definition 4.1. A $\mathbf{PC}$-category is a category enriched in the multicategory $\underline{Perm}$. Similarly, a $\mathbf{PC}$-functor is an enriched functor, and a $\mathbf{PC}$-natural transformation is an enriched natural transformation.
Définition 5.2. Soit $F$ un $\mathcal{C}_{T}$-module à gauche. On dit qu’il est de dimension cohomologique $n$ si pour tout $\mathcal{C}_{T}$-module $G$, et pour tout $m>n$, on a l’égalité $\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{m}\left(F,G\right)=0$, et s’il existe un $\mathcal{C}$-module $G$ tel que l’on ait $\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}_{T}}^{n}\left(F,G\right)\neq 0.$
Définition 4.2. Un objet de $\mathcal{C}_{T}\mathrm{-mod}$ est de type fini s’il est quotient d’une somme finie de projectifs $T$-standards.
Définition 7.1. Une petite catégorie $\mathcal{C}$ est à dualité si le $\mathcal{C}$-module $\underline{\mathbb{Z}}$ est à dualité. Dans ce cas on a un isomorphisme naturel $\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{i}\left(\underline{\mathbb{Z}},-\right)\cong% \operatorname{Tor}^{\mathcal{C}}_{n-i}\left(D^{n}\left(\underline{\mathbb{Z}}% \right),-\right)$ pour un certain entier $n$. On appelle le $\mathcal{C}$-modules à droite $D^{n}\left(\underline{\mathbb{Z}}\right)$ le dualisant de $\mathcal{C}$.
Définition 3.2. Un bifoncteur de Yoneda pour $\mathcal{C}$ est un bifoncteur $T:\mathcal{C}^{op}\times\mathcal{C}\to k\mathrm{-mod}$ muni d’une surjection $\mu:\underline{\underline{\mathcal{C}}}\xymatrix{\ar@{->>}[r]&}T$ telle que le morphisme canonique entre éléments de ${(\mathcal{C}^{op}\times\mathcal{C})}\mathrm{-mod}$ $\varphi:\left[(a,b)\mapsto\textup{Hom}_{{\mathcal{C}}\mathrm{-mod}}(T_{b},T_{a% })\right]\to\left[(a,b)\mapsto T(a,b)\right]$ défini par $\varphi_{(a,b)}(F)=F_{b}(\mu_{b,b}(\mathbf{1}_{b}))$ soit un isomorphisme.
Définition 5.6. On appelle foncteur à dualité un foncteur qui satisfait une des conditions du théorème.
Définition 4.10. Soit $\mathcal{A}$ une catégorie $k$-linéaire. Une dualité de Serre pour $\mathcal{A}$ est un endofoncteur $S:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{A}$ muni d’un isomorphisme naturel $\Phi_{a,b}:\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(b,Sa)\rightarrow\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A% }}(a,b)^{\prime}$ pour touts objets $a,b$ de $\mathcal{A}$. [Comparer à [RV02]]
Définition 1.1. Soit $\mathcal{C}$ une petite catégorie. On dit qu’elle est à dualité s’il existe un foncteur $D:\mathcal{C}^{op}\rightarrow\mathbf{Ab}$, un entier $n$, et un isomorphisme naturel $\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{i}\left(\underline{\mathbb{Z}},-\right)\cong% \operatorname{Tor}^{\mathcal{C}}_{n-i}\left(D,-\right)$ où $\underline{\mathbb{Z}}$ désigne le foncteur constant.
Définition 5.4. On appelle foncteur d’Eilenberg-Mac Lane de degré $n$ un objet $F$ de $\mathcal{C}_{T}\mathrm{-mod}$ tel que l’on ait un isomorphisme $RD\left(F\right)\cong D^{n}\left(F\right)[n]$ dans $\mathcal{D}^{+}\left(\mathcal{C}_{T^{op}}\mathrm{-mod}\right)$ (On rappelle que $D^{n}\left(F\right)=H^{n}(RDF)$).
Définition 4.8. On dit qu’un complexe $X$ de $\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{C}_{T}\mathrm{-mod})$ est parfait s’il est quasi-isomorphe à un complexe borné de projectifs de type fini.
Définition 7.15. Un immeuble sphérique est un complexe simplicial qui est l’union de sous-complexes $\Sigma_{i}$ vérifiant (1) Chaque $\Sigma_{i}$ est un complexe de Coxeter fini. (2) Pour touts simplexes $A,B\in\Delta$, il existe un appartement $\Sigma_{i}$ contenant $A$ et $B$. (3) Si $\Sigma_{1}$ et $\Sigma_{2}$ sont deux appartements contenant $A$ et $B$, il existe un isomorphisme $\Sigma_{1}\rightarrow\Sigma_{2}$ fixant $A$ et $B$.
Définition 5.1. On dit qu’un $\mathcal{C}_{T}$-module est de type $FP_{\infty}$ (resp. de type $FP$) s’il admet une résolution (resp. une résolution finie) par des projectifs de type fini de $\mathcal{C}_{T}\mathrm{-mod}$.
Définition 3.9. Soit $B$ une catégorie et $A$ une sous-catégorie pleine. On dit que $A$ est épiréflexive si l’inclusion de $i:A\rightarrow B$ admet un adjoint à gauche $t:B\rightarrow A$ tel que l’unité de l’adjonction est un épimorphisme.
Définitions 2.1. — Un $\mathcal{C}$-module à gauche (resp. à droite) est un foncteur covariant de $\mathcal{C}$ (resp. $\mathcal{C}^{op}$) dans la catégorie ${k}\mathrm{-mod}$. — On note $I$ la catégorie $0\rightarrow 1$. Soient $F$ et $G$ deux $\mathcal{C}$-modules à gauche. Une transformation naturelle entre $F$ et $G$ est un foncteur $T:\mathcal{C}\times I\rightarrow k\mathrm{-mod}$ tel que $T(c,0)=F(c)$ et $T(c,1)=G(c)$. — On note ${\mathcal{C}}\mathrm{-mod}$ (resp. ${\mathcal{C}^{\text{op}}}\mathrm{-mod}$) la catégorie dont les objets sont les $\mathcal{C}$-modules à gauche (resp. à droite) et dont les morphismes sont les transformations naturelles.
Definition B.15. Let $F$ be a frame. A congruence $\theta$ on $F$ is an equivalence relation on $F$ that preserves finite meets and arbitrary joins. That is, if $a_{1},a_{2},b_{1},b_{2}\in F$ such that $a_{1}\theta b_{1}$ and $a_{2}\theta b_{2}$, then $(a_{1}\wedge a_{2})\theta(b_{1}\wedge b_{2})$, and if $\{a_{i}\}_{i\in I},\{b_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ are families in $F$ for some index set $I$ such that $a_{i}\theta b_{i}$ for each $i\in I$, then we have $\left(\bigvee_{i\in I}a_{i}\right)\theta\left(\bigvee_{i\in I}b_{i}\right)$. If $\theta$ also preserves arbitrary meets, i.e. if given the same families $\{a_{i}\}$ and $\{b_{i}\}$ as above, then $\left(\bigwedge_{i\in I}a_{i}\right)\theta\left(\bigwedge_{i\in I}b_{i}\right)$, we say that $\theta$ is a complete frame congruence. The set of all congruences on a frame $F$ is denoted by $\mathrm{Con}(F)$, which can be ordered by inclusion: $\theta\leq\varphi$ if and only if $\theta\subseteq\varphi$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a poset and $X\subseteq\mathbf{P}$ a subset. For any other subset $A\subseteq\mathbf{P}$, we shall use the notation $\bar{}{\downarrow\,}A={\downarrow\,}A\cap X$. In the same way, $\bar{}{\uparrow\,}A$ is defined as the set ${\uparrow\,}A\cap X$.
Definition 5.12. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a poset and $X$ a downwards directed subset of $\mathbf{P}$. For each subset $Y$ of $X$, we define $L_{X,Y}$ to be the extension on $\mathbf{P}$ of the derived Grothendieck topology induced by $Y\subseteq X$ on $X$, which we denote by $K_{Y}^{X}$.
Definition 4.4. Let $(\mathbf{P},J)$ and $(\mathbf{Q},K)$ be sites. Then an order isomorphism $\varphi:\mathbf{P}\to\mathbf{Q}$ is called an isomorphism of sites if it satisfies one of the following equivalent conditions: 1. $\varphi$ preserves covers and has the clp; 2. $\varphi$ and $\varphi^{-1}$ both preserve covers; 3. $\varphi$ and $\varphi^{-1}$ both have the clp.
Definition B.4. Let $X$ be a topological space. Then a non-empty closed subset $F$ of $X$ is called irreducible if for each closed sets $F_{1}$ and $F_{2}$ such that $F=F_{1}\cup F_{2}$, we have $F_{1}=F$ or $F_{2}=F$. Then $X$ is called sober when each irreducible closed subset is the closure of a unique point of $X$.
Definition 1.1. A poset $(\mathbf{P},\leq)$ is a set $\mathbf{P}$ equipped with a (partial) order $\leq$. That is, $\leq$, is binary relation, which is reflexive, antisymmetric and transitive. We often write $\mathbf{P}$ instead of $(\mathbf{P},\leq)$ if it is clear which order is used. If either $p\leq q$ or $q\leq p$ for each $p,q\in\mathbf{P}$, we say that $\leq$ is a linear order, and we call $\mathbf{P}$ a linearly ordered set. Given a poset $\mathbf{P}$ with order $\leq$, we define the opposite poset $\mathbf{P}^{\mathrm{op}}$ as the poset with the same underlying set $\mathbf{P}$, but where $p\leq q$ if and only if $q\leq p$ in the original order. .
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a poset. Given an element $p\in\mathbf{P}$, a subset $S\subseteq\mathbf{P}$ is called a sieve on $p$ if $S\in\mathcal{D}({\downarrow\,}p)$, where ${\downarrow\,}p=\{q\in\mathbf{P}:q\leq p\}$. Equivalently, $S$ is a sieve on $p$ if $q\leq p$ for each $q\in S$ and $r\in S$ if $r\leq q$ for some $q\in S$. Then a Grothendieck topology $J$ on $\mathbf{P}$ is a map $p\mapsto J(p)$ that assigns to each element $p\in\mathbf{P}$ a collection $J(p)$ of sieves on $p$ such that 1. the maximal sieve ${\downarrow\,}p$ is an element of $J(p)$; 2. if $S\in J(p)$ and $q\leq p$, then $S\cap{\downarrow\,}q\in J(q)$; 3. if $S\in J(p)$ and $R$ is any sieve on $p$ such that $R\cap{\downarrow\,}q\in J(q)$ for each $q\in S$, then $R\in J(p)$. The second and third axioms are called the stability axiom and the transitivity axiom, respectively. Given $p\in\mathbf{P}$, we refer to elements of $J(p)$ as $J$-covers of $p$. A pair $(\mathbf{P},J)$ consisting of a poset $\mathbf{P}$ and a Grothendieck topology $J$ on $\mathbf{P}$ is called a site. We denote the set of Grothendieck topologies on $\mathbf{P}$ by $\mathcal{G}(\mathbf{P})$. This set can be ordered pointwisely: for any two Grothendieck topologies $J$ and $K$ on $\mathbf{P}$ we define $J\leq K$ if $J(p)\subseteq K(p)$ for each $p\in\mathbf{P}$.
Definition 1.9. Let $\mathbf{P}$, $\mathbf{Q}$ be posets and $f:\mathbf{P}\to\mathbf{Q}$, $g:\mathbf{Q}\to\mathbf{P}$ order morphism. If $f(p)\leq q$ if and only if $p\leq g(q)$ holds for each $p\in\mathbf{P}$ and $q\in\mathbf{Q}$, then $g$ is called the upper adjoint of $f$ and $f$ is called the lower adjoint of $g$. If the upper adjoint of $f$ exists, it is sometimes denoted by $f_{*}$. Similarly, the lower adjoint of $g$, if it exists, is sometimes denoted by $g^{*}$.
Definition 1.18. The category $\mathbf{Frm}$ of frames is the category with frames as objects and frame morphisms as morphisms. The category $\mathbf{cHA}$ of complete Heyting algebras is defined as the category with frames as objects and as morphisms exactly the frame morphisms $f:H\to G$ which also satisfy $f(x\to y)=f(x)\to f(y)$ for each $x,y\in H$. Finally, the category $\mathbf{Loc}$ of locales is defined as the opposite category of $\mathbf{Frm}$. That is, the objects of $\mathbf{Loc}$ are frames, and $f:L\to K$ is a locale morphism if it is the opposite of a frame morphism $K\to L$. If we want to stress that we work in the $\mathbf{Loc}$, we call the objects locales rather than frames.
Definition A.5. Let $X$ be a topological space with topology $\mathcal{O}(X)$. Then $X$ is called Noetherian if $\mathcal{O}(X)$ ordered by inclusion is Noetherian.
Definition 4.1. [24, Section VII.10] Let $(\mathbf{P},J)$ and $(\mathbf{Q},K)$ be sites. An order morphism $\varphi:\mathbf{P}\to\mathbf{Q}$ preserves covers if ${\downarrow\,}\varphi[S]\in K(\varphi(p))$ for each $p\in\mathbf{P}$ and each $S\in J(p)$. An order morphism $\pi:\mathbf{Q}\to\mathbf{P}$ has the covering lifting property (abbreviated by “clp”) if for each $q\in\mathbf{Q}$ and each $S\in J(\pi(q))$ there is an $R\in K(q)$ such that $\pi[R]\subseteq S$.
Definition 5.4. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a downwards directed poset. Even if $\mathbf{P}$ already has a least element, we can add a new least element, which we denote by $0$. We define $\mathbf{P}_{0}=\mathbf{P}\cup\{0\}$, where $0<p$ for each $p\in\mathbf{P}$. If $A\subseteq\mathbf{P}$, then we write $A_{0}=A\cup\{0\}$. If $p\in\mathbf{P}$, then ${\downarrow\,}p$ with respect to $\mathbf{P}_{0}$ is exactly $({\downarrow\,}p)_{0}$, where ${\downarrow\,}p$ is defined with respect to $\mathbf{P}$. If $X\subseteq\mathbf{P}$, then $X\cap{\downarrow\,}p=X\cap({\downarrow\,}p)_{0}$, in which case the notation does not matter. If $J$ is a topology on $\mathbf{P}$ and we want to define a similar topology on $\mathbf{P}_{0}$, we denote this topology by $J^{0}$. For instance, $K^{0}_{X}$ is the derived topology on $\mathbf{P}_{0}$ with respect to $X$. By the previous remark about $X\cap{\downarrow\,}p=X\cap({\downarrow\,}p)_{0}$, we have $S\in J_{X}^{0}(p)$ if and only if $X\cap{\downarrow\,}p\subseteq S$.
Definition 1.4. Let $M$ be a non-empty subset of a poset $\mathbf{P}$. 1. An element $x\in M$ such that ${\uparrow\,}x\cap M=\{x\}$ is called a maximal element. The set of maximal elements of $M$ is denoted by $\max M$. The set of all minimal elements $\min M$ is defined dually. 2. If there is an element $x\in M$ such that $x\geq y$ for each $y\in M$, we call $x$ the greatest element of $M$, which is necesarrily unique. The least element of $M$ is defined dually. If $\mathbf{P}$ itself has a greatest element, it is denoted by $1$. Dually, the least element of $\mathbf{P}$ is denoted by $0$. 3. An element $x\in\mathbf{P}$ is called an upper bound of $M$ if $y\leq x$ for each $y\in M$. If the set of upper bounds of $M$ has a least element, it is called the join of $M$, which is necesarrily unique and is denoted by $\bigvee M$. Dually, we can define lower bounds and the meet of $M$, which is denoted by $\bigwedge M$. The (binary) join and the (binary) meet of $\{x,y\}$ are denoted by $x\vee y$ and $x\wedge y$, respectively. 4. $M$ is called upwards (downwards) directed if for every $x,y\in M$ there is an upper (lower) bound $z\in M$. 5. $M$ is called a filter if $M\in\mathcal{U}(\mathbf{P})$ and $M$ is downwards directed. We denote the set of filters of $\mathbf{P}$ by $\mathcal{F}(\mathbf{P})$. A filter is called principal if it is equal to ${\uparrow\,}p$ for some $p\in\mathbf{P}$. 6. $M$ is called an ideal if $M\in\mathcal{D}(\mathbf{P})$ and $M$ is upwards directed. We denote the set of ideals of $\mathbf{P}$ by $\mathrm{Idl}(\mathbf{P})$. An ideal is called principal if it is equal to ${\downarrow\,}p$ for some $p\in\mathbf{P}$.
Definition B.10. Let $L$ be a locale. A subset $M\subseteq L$ is called a sublocale if it is closed under all meets and if $x\to m\in M$ for each $x\in L$ and each $m\in M$2If we had defined sublocales of a locale $L$ to be subsets that are closed under finite meets and arbitrary joins, we would have obtained the wrong definition, since these subsets describe subframes rather than sublocales.. We denote the set of all sublocales a locale $L$ by $\mathrm{Sub}(L)$, which can be ordered by inclusion.
Definition 4.21. Let $J$ be a Grothendieck topology on a category $\mathcal{C}$. Then $J$ is called subcanonical if all representable presheaves are $J$-sheaves. That is, if $\mathbf{y}(C)=\mathrm{Hom}(-,C)$ is a $J$-sheaf for each $C\in\mathcal{C}$. The canonical topology on $\mathcal{C}$ is the finest subcanonical topology.
Definition C.2. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a poset and $X,Y$ subsets of $\mathbf{P}$. Then we define the Heyting implication $X\to Y=\bigcup\{A\in\mathcal{D}(\mathbf{P}):A\cap X\subseteq Y\}.$
Definition B.1. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a poset. Then the collection $\mathcal{D}(\mathbf{P})$ of down-sets of $\mathbf{P}$ is a topology on $\mathbf{P}$, called the Alexandrov topology on $\mathbf{P}$.
Definition 1.7. Let $\mathbf{P},\mathbf{Q}$ be posets and $f:\mathbf{P}\to\mathbf{Q}$ a map. Then $f$ is called 1. an order morphism if $x\leq y$ implies $f(x)\leq f(y)$ for each $x,y\in\mathbf{P}$; 2. a embedding of posets if $f(x)\leq f(y)$ if and only if $x\leq y$ for each $x,y\in\mathbf{P}$; 3. a meet-semilattice morphism if $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ are both meet-semilattices and $f(x\wedge y)=f(x)\wedge f(y)$ for each $x,y\in\mathbf{P}$; 4. a lattice morphism if $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ are both lattices and $f$ is a meet-semilattice morphism such that $f(x\vee y)=f(x)\vee f(y)$ for each $x,y\in\mathbf{P}$; 5. a frame morphism if $\mathbf{P}$ and $\mathbf{Q}$ are both frames and $f\left(\bigvee M\right)=\bigvee f(M)$, $f\left(\bigwedge N\right)=\bigwedge f(N)$ for each $M\subseteq\mathbf{P}$ and each finite $N\subseteq\mathbf{P}$. An order morphism, meet-semilattice morphism, lattice morphism, frame morphism is called an order isomorphism, meet-semilattice isomorphism, lattice isormphism, frame isomorphism, respectively, if there is a morphism $g:\mathbf{Q}\to\mathbf{P}$ of the same type such that $f\circ g=1_{\mathbf{Q}}$ and $g\circ f=1_{\mathbf{P}}$.
Definition 5.7. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a downwards directed poset and take $X\subseteq\mathbf{P}$ such that ${\uparrow\,}X\neq\mathbf{P}$. Given a fixed $p_{0}\in({\uparrow\,}X)^{c}$, define $E_{0}:\mathrm{Sh}(\mathbf{P},K_{X})\to\mathrm{Sh}(\mathbf{P}_{0},K_{X}^{0})$ as follows. $E_{0}$ acts on $F\in\mathrm{Sh}(\mathbf{P},K_{X})$ by $F\mapsto\bar{F}$, where $\bar{F}$ acts on objects of $\mathbf{P}_{0}$ by $\bar{F}(p)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}F(p),&p\neq 0;\\ F(p_{0}),&p=0,\end{array}\right.$ and acts on morphisms by $\bar{F}(q\leq p)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}F(q\leq p),&q\neq 0;\\ F(r\leq p_{0})^{-1}F(r\leq p),&q=0\mathrm{\ for\ some\ }r\leq p,p_{0}\mathrm{% \ in\ }\mathbf{P}.\end{array}\right.$ Furthermore, if $\alpha:F\to G$ in $\mathrm{Sh}(\mathbf{P},K_{X})$, then $E_{0}$ acts on $\alpha$ by $\alpha\mapsto\bar{\alpha}$, where $\bar{\alpha}_{p}=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}\alpha_{p},&p\neq 0;\\ \alpha_{p_{0}},&p=0.\end{array}\right.$
Definition 1.5. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a poset. Then $\mathbf{P}$ is called 1. Artinian (Noetherian) if every non-empty subset contains a minimal (maximal) element; 2. a meet-semilattice (join-semilattice) if all binary meets (joins) exist; 3. a lattice if all binary meets and binary joins exist; 4. a complete lattice if all meets and joins exist. 5. a distributive lattice if it is a lattice such that the distributive law $x\wedge(y\vee z)=(x\wedge y)\vee(x\wedge z)$ holds for each $x,y,z\in\mathbf{P}$ 6. a frame if all joins and all finite meets exists and the infinite distributive law $x\wedge\bigvee_{i}y_{i}=\bigvee_{i}(x\wedge y_{i})$ holds for each element $x$ and each family $y_{i}$ in $\mathbf{P}$.
Definition 1.16. The element $g_{x}(y)$ as defined in the previous example is denoted by $x\to y$ and is called the relative pseudo-complement of $x$ with respect to $y$. We refer to the map $F\times F\to F$ given by $(x,y)\mapsto(x\to y)$ as the Heyting implication or Heyting operator. So we have $x\wedge z\leq y\ \mathrm{if\ and\ only\ if\ }z\leq(x\to y).$ For each $x\in F$ we denote the element $x\to 0$ by $\neg x$, which we call the negation of $x$.
Definition 1.2. Let $(\mathbf{P},\leq)$ be a poset and $M\subseteq\mathbf{P}$ a subset. We say that $M$ is an up-set if for each $x\in M$ and $y\in\mathbf{P}$ we have $x\leq y$ implies $y\in M$. Similarly, $M$ is called a down-set if for each $x\in M$ and $y\in\mathbf{P}$ we have $x\geq y$ implies $y\in M$. Given an element $x\in\mathbf{P}$, we define the up-set and down-set generated by $x$ by ${\uparrow\,}x=\{y\in\mathbf{P}:y\geq x\}$ and ${\downarrow\,}x=\{y\in\mathbf{P}:y\leq x\}$, respectively. We can also define the up-set generated by a subset $M$ of $\mathbf{P}$ by ${\uparrow\,}M=\{x\in\mathbf{P}:x\geq m$ for some $m\in M\}=\bigcup_{m\in M}{\uparrow\,}m$, and similarly, we define the down-set generated by $M$ by ${\downarrow\,}M=\bigcup_{m\in M}{\downarrow\,}m$. We denote the collection of all up-sets of a poset $\mathbf{P}$ by $\mathcal{U}(\mathbf{P})$ and the set of all down-sets by $\mathcal{D}(\mathbf{P})$. If we want to emphasize that we use the order $\leq$, we write $\mathcal{U}(\mathbf{P},\leq)$ instead of $\mathcal{U}(\mathbf{P})$.
Definition 2.5. Let $J$ be a Grothendieck topology on a poset $\mathbf{P}$. We say that $J$ is complete if for each $p\in\mathbf{P}$ and each family $\{S_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ in $J(p)$, for some index set $I$, we have $\bigcap_{i\in I}S_{i}\in J(p)$.
Definition B.6. A nucleus on a locale (or more general, a meet-semilattice) $L$ is a function $j:L\to L$ that satisfies, for all $a,b\in L$: (i) $a\leq j(a)$; (ii) $j\circ j(a)=j(a)$ (iii) $j(a\wedge b)=j(a)\wedge j(b)$. If $j$ also satisfies the stronger condition (iii’) $j\left(\bigwedge_{i\in I}a_{i}\right)=\bigwedge_{i\in I}j(a_{i})$, for each family $\{a_{i}\}_{i\in I}\subseteq L$ with $I$ an index set, then we say that $j$ is complete. The set of all nuclei on a locale $L$ is denoted by $\mathrm{Nuc}(L)$, which can be ordered as follows. If $j,k\in\mathrm{Nuc}(L)$, then we define $j\leq k$ if $j(a)\leq k(a)$ for each $a\in L$.
Definition 4.10. [24, Chapter III.4] Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a poset and $J$ a Grothendieck topology on $\mathbf{P}$. Furthermore, let $F:\mathbf{P}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathbf{Sets}$ be a functor (a contravariant functor to $\mathbf{Sets}$ is also called a presheaf). Let $p\in\mathbf{P}$ and $S\in J(p)$. Then a family $\langle a_{x}\rangle_{x\in S}\in\prod_{x\in S}F(x)$ is called a matching family for the cover $S$ with elements of $F$ if $F(y\leq x)a_{x}=a_{y}$ for each $x,y\in S$ such that $y\leq x$. An element $a\in F(p)$ such that $F(x\leq p)a=a_{x}$ for each $x\in S$ is called an amalgamation. We say that $F$ is a $J$-sheaf if for each $p\in\mathbf{P}$ for each $S\in J(p)$ and for each matching family $\langle a_{x}\rangle_{x\in S}$ there is a unique amalgamation $a\in F(p)$.
